│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The provided reproducer crashes with a SIGSEGV while running the              │
│ nary-reassociate pass, but the crash is actually triggered in ScalarEvolution │
│ during guard (assume/branch/guard intrinsic) collection and use when          │
│ computing ranges. The backtrace shows extremely deep and repeated recursion:  │
│ - ScalarEvolution::LoopGuards::collectFromBlock -> CollectCondition ->        │
│ getSMinExpr.                                                                  │
│ - getSMinExpr -> getMinMaxExpr -> isKnownViaNonRecursiveReasoning ->          │
│ getSignedRange -> getRangeRef -> getRangeForAffineNoSelfWrappingAR ->         │
│ applyLoopGuards -> LoopGuards::collect -> collectFromBlock -> … (recurses).   │
│ This creates re-entrancy into applyLoopGuards while we are actively           │
│ collecting loop guards, leading to unbounded recursion. Eventually, the stack │
│ is corrupted, and the observed fault happens inside ConstantInt::get during   │
│ constant folding (incidental to the recursion), not because of a direct       │
│ constant IR bug.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - The initial ScalarEvolution dump shows an addrec and attempts at range      │
│ sharpening (expensive range sharpening option enabled).                       │
│ - The first transformation point provided by the user lands at                │
│ ValueSymbolTable::lookup() due to querying whether llvm.experimental.guard    │
│ exists. This is a symptom of LoopGuards::collect querying guards, not a       │
│ faulty mutation.                                                              │
│ - The stack shows repeated calls to Intrinsic::getDeclarationIfExists         │
│ (checking for guard decl) and then repeated loops of SCEV min/max reasoning   │
│ which uses applyLoopGuards, inducing recursion.                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ LoopGuards::collect builds rewrite maps by calling SCEV builders (e.g.,       │
│ getSMinExpr/UMaxExpr). Those builders internally perform reasoning            │
│ (getMinMaxExpr) that computes ranges via                                      │
│ getRangeRef/getRangeForAffineNoSelfWrappingAR. The latter calls               │
│ ScalarEvolution::applyLoopGuards to refine SCEV ranges using loop guards. But │
│ applyLoopGuards calls LoopGuards::collect again, re-entering guard collection │
│ while it is still in progress. There is no reentrancy guard for this, unlike  │
│ other parts of ScalarEvolution (e.g., Pending* sets for other recursion       │
│ breakers). In the provided IR, this causes large recursion, ultimately        │
│ overflowing and crashing.                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ So the bug is a missing re-entrancy guard in ScalarEvolution::applyLoopGuards │
│ to avoid recursively collecting guards while guard collection already runs.   │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                     │
│ - File: llvm/include/llvm/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.h, add a private boolean   │
│ reentrancy flag to ScalarEvolution to block recursive applyLoopGuards         │
│ invocations.                                                                  │
│   Insert after the existing recursion/processing state booleans:              │
│   + Add: `bool InApplyLoopGuards = false;` with a comment.                    │
│                                                                               │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp, modify applyLoopGuards         │
│ overloads to short-circuit if re-entered and to set/restore the flag during   │
│ normal execution.                                                             │
│   Edit 1 (lines 15969-15976): wrap the applyLoopGuards(const SCEV*, const     │
│ Loop*) body with a reentrancy guard:                                          │
│     if (InApplyLoopGuards) return Expr;                                       │
│     bool Old = InApplyLoopGuards; InApplyLoopGuards = true;                   │
│     const SCEV *Res = applyLoopGuards(Expr, LoopGuards::collect(L, *this));   │
│     InApplyLoopGuards = Old;                                                  │
│     return Res;                                                               │
│                                                                               │
│   Edit 2 (lines 15973-15976): similarly guard the overload                    │
│ applyLoopGuards(const SCEV*, const LoopGuards&):                              │
│     if (InApplyLoopGuards) return Expr;                                       │
│     return Guards.rewrite(Expr);                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ These changes ensure that once we enter applyLoopGuards, any nested calls     │
│ resulting from SCEV builder reasoning while collecting guards will just       │
│ return the original expression and will not recursively attempt to collect    │
│ guards again. This breaks the recursion loop safely without affecting normal  │
│ guard application outside of collection.                                      │
│                                                                               │
│ NOTICE: We avoid changing LoopGuards::collect itself (which is not a friend   │
│ of ScalarEvolution) and we avoid altering SCEV builder routines. The minimal  │
│ and safe fix is to provide a reentrancy guard in applyLoopGuards.             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is caused by uncontrolled re-entrancy: applyLoopGuards is called    │
│ while guard collection is still running, leading to infinite recursion and    │
│ stack overflow. By adding a simple in-progress flag (InApplyLoopGuards) and   │
│ early-out in applyLoopGuards, we prevent re-entrancy, thus avoiding unbounded │
│ recursion and the subsequent crash. The functional effect is that during      │
│ guard collection, we do not recursively apply loop guards while building SCEV │
│ expressions used for the guard rewrite; this is safe and should not regress   │
│ correctness, while it resolves the crash.                                     │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
