  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe provided reproducer crashes
with a SIGSEGV while running the nary-reassociate pass, but the crash is actually
triggered in ScalarEvolution during guard (assume/branch/guard intrinsic)
collection and use when computing ranges. The backtrace shows extremely deep and
repeated recursion:\n- ScalarEvolution::LoopGuards::collectFromBlock ->
CollectCondition -> getSMinExpr.\n- getSMinExpr -> getMinMaxExpr ->
isKnownViaNonRecursiveReasoning -> getSignedRange -> getRangeRef ->
getRangeForAffineNoSelfWrappingAR -> applyLoopGuards -> LoopGuards::collect ->
collectFromBlock -> \u2026 (recurses).\nThis creates re-entrancy into
applyLoopGuards while we are actively collecting loop guards, leading to
unbounded recursion. Eventually, the stack is corrupted, and the observed fault
happens inside ConstantInt::get during constant folding (incidental to the
recursion), not because of a direct constant IR bug.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\n- The initial ScalarEvolution dump shows an addrec and attempts at range
sharpening (expensive range sharpening option enabled).\n- The first
transformation point provided by the user lands at ValueSymbolTable::lookup() due
to querying whether llvm.experimental.guard exists. This is a symptom of
LoopGuards::collect querying guards, not a faulty mutation.\n- The stack shows
repeated calls to Intrinsic::getDeclarationIfExists (checking for guard decl) and
then repeated loops of SCEV min/max reasoning which uses applyLoopGuards,
inducing recursion.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nLoopGuards::collect builds
rewrite maps by calling SCEV builders (e.g., getSMinExpr/UMaxExpr). Those
builders internally perform reasoning (getMinMaxExpr) that computes ranges via
getRangeRef/getRangeForAffineNoSelfWrappingAR. The latter calls
ScalarEvolution::applyLoopGuards to refine SCEV ranges using loop guards. But
applyLoopGuards calls LoopGuards::collect again, re-entering guard collection
while it is still in progress. There is no reentrancy guard for this, unlike
other parts of ScalarEvolution (e.g., Pending* sets for other recursion
breakers). In the provided IR, this causes large recursion, ultimately
overflowing and crashing.\n\nSo the bug is a missing re-entrancy guard in
ScalarEvolution::applyLoopGuards to avoid recursively collecting guards while
guard collection already runs.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:
llvm/include/llvm/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.h, add a private boolean reentrancy
flag to ScalarEvolution to block recursive applyLoopGuards invocations.\n  Insert
after the existing recursion/processing state booleans:\n  + Add: `bool
InApplyLoopGuards = false;` with a comment.\n\n- File:
llvm/lib/Analysis/ScalarEvolution.cpp, modify applyLoopGuards overloads to
short-circuit if re-entered and to set/restore the flag during normal
execution.\n  Edit 1 (lines 15969-15976): wrap the applyLoopGuards(const SCEV*,
const Loop*) body with a reentrancy guard:\n    if (InApplyLoopGuards) return
Expr;\n    bool Old = InApplyLoopGuards; InApplyLoopGuards = true;\n    const
SCEV *Res = applyLoopGuards(Expr, LoopGuards::collect(L, *this));\n
InApplyLoopGuards = Old;\n    return Res;\n\n  Edit 2 (lines 15973-15976):
similarly guard the overload applyLoopGuards(const SCEV*, const LoopGuards&):\n
if (InApplyLoopGuards) return Expr;\n    return Guards.rewrite(Expr);\n\nThese
changes ensure that once we enter applyLoopGuards, any nested calls resulting
from SCEV builder reasoning while collecting guards will just return the original
expression and will not recursively attempt to collect guards again. This breaks
the recursion loop safely without affecting normal guard application outside of
collection.\n\nNOTICE: We avoid changing LoopGuards::collect itself (which is not
a friend of ScalarEvolution) and we avoid altering SCEV builder routines. The
minimal and safe fix is to provide a reentrancy guard in applyLoopGuards.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by uncontrolled re-entrancy: applyLoopGuards is
called while guard collection is still running, leading to infinite recursion and
stack overflow. By adding a simple in-progress flag (InApplyLoopGuards) and
early-out in applyLoopGuards, we prevent re-entrancy, thus avoiding unbounded
recursion and the subsequent crash. The functional effect is that during guard
collection, we do not recursively apply loop guards while building SCEV
expressions used for the guard rewrite; this is safe and should not regress
correctness, while it resolves the crash.",
